WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.080 --> 00:00:09.460
&gt;&gt;Susan Wojcicki: So good morning.
So I'm very, very pleased to have Marlee Matlin here.

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:12.769
And I'm very pleased to introduce her and

00:00:12.769 --> 00:00:17.670
have her come up here and tell us her story and tell us about some

00:00:17.670 --> 00:00:23.619
of the causes that she is committed to.
[ Applause ]

00:00:23.619 --> 00:00:30.619
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Thank you.
Thank you, thank you, Susan.

00:00:31.070 --> 00:00:33.820
And speaking of not everyone knowing who I
am, it's true.

00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:36.510
There isn't.
I don't know if any of you -- well, I have

00:00:36.510 --> 00:00:42.409
to admit this, but I was a huge -- I actually
had a huge weakness, when I have the time

00:00:42.409 --> 00:00:46.010
to watch a little television, because I have
four kids, and it's difficult to watch.

00:00:46.010 --> 00:00:51.089
And I have one teenaged girl who is 14, and
she's a huge fan of "The Bachelor."

00:00:51.089 --> 00:00:56.040
You all know the show "The Bachelor."
It just so happened that on "Dancing with

00:00:56.040 --> 00:01:00.479
the Stars" when I was there, I happened to
meet the -- what's his name?

00:01:00.479 --> 00:01:07.010
Jake -- I actually met Vienna, who is the
woman who grabbed Jake, or who Jake chose

00:01:07.010 --> 00:01:11.140
on this year's bachelor.
And she came up to me and said, "Are you an

00:01:11.140 --> 00:01:14.150
actress?"
And, of course, clearly, it proves that not

00:01:14.150 --> 00:01:16.200
everybody knows who I am.
[ Laughter ]

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:23.200
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Anyway, I am so happy to
be here today at the coolest place, the mecca

00:01:24.770 --> 00:01:29.710
of the Internet world, Google.
Google is a sign -- what's the sign?

00:01:29.710 --> 00:01:34.830
This is the sign -- Google headquarters.
It's like that moment when Darth Vader said,

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:41.830
"Luke, I am your father."
And everyone gasped and said, "No way!"

00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:47.330
I can't believe it's happening.
It's the ultimate cool to be here today.

00:01:47.330 --> 00:01:50.550
And there's free food, too.
You guys have free Red Bull, free food.

00:01:50.550 --> 00:01:52.180
I can't believe it.
It's really great.

00:01:52.180 --> 00:01:55.990
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: So is there a resume that

00:01:55.990 --> 00:01:57.860
I need to give you if I want to apply for
a job here?

00:01:57.860 --> 00:01:59.490
Maybe I could play pool all day.
I don't know.

00:01:59.490 --> 00:02:03.280
Anyway, thank you.
It's a fun place to be.

00:02:03.280 --> 00:02:07.560
Thank you for having me here.
More importantly, being here with you, I can

00:02:07.560 --> 00:02:13.670
finally see some of the faces behind the news
and the entertainment and the information

00:02:13.670 --> 00:02:19.620
that the world has come to rely upon.
And now that I see you, I want to say thank

00:02:19.620 --> 00:02:23.260
you for all that you are doing.
You are fantastic.

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:29.600
Thank you very much.
Well, I know that you're anxious to have me

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:34.480
talk about my book, that book that is called
"I'll Scream Later."

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:37.090
And some of you may wonder where that title
came from.

00:02:37.090 --> 00:02:41.819
Well, I have to admit that if you didn't know
already, I am a recovering drug addict.

00:02:41.819 --> 00:02:47.069
And today it's been 23 years, two months,
and 20 days.

00:02:47.069 --> 00:02:48.400
And just --
[ Applause ]

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:50.870
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Thank you.
[ Applause ]

00:02:50.870 --> 00:02:57.870
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: And just after I won the
Golden Globe for best actress in "Children

00:02:58.569 --> 00:03:02.950
of a Lesser God," I checked myself into rehab
at the Betty Ford Clinic.

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:09.950
Unlike today, where my entire journey would
have been covered by TMZ and Perez Hilton,

00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:16.980
back then, way back then, there was no such
thing as being able to -- there was no such

00:03:16.989 --> 00:03:19.400
thing as those things, so I was able to check
in in secret.

00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:23.700
While I was there, I was nominated for an
Academy Award for best actress.

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:28.640
If you can imagine, I must be the only person
to get that, "Congratulations, you've been

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:33.680
nominated," call while working on my sobriety
at the Betty Ford Clinic.

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:39.879
So, anyway, when the phone call came in from
Jack here, who -- by the way, this is Jack

00:03:39.879 --> 00:03:42.790
Jason, my interpreter, if I didn't introduce
him already, sorry.

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:47.290
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: I don't have a male voice.

00:03:47.290 --> 00:03:49.069
I just wanted to let you know that.
[ Laughter ]

00:03:49.069 --> 00:03:52.819
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Well, maybe after a couple
of cigarettes.

00:03:52.819 --> 00:03:59.160
No, anyway.
Anyway, he asked me for reaction or a statement,

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:03.709
which wasn't going to be, "Staying sober.
Thank you for the nomination, but I'm staying

00:04:03.709 --> 00:04:06.410
sober, keeping sober."
I didn't want to say that.

00:04:06.410 --> 00:04:12.459
So instead, I said, tell them I'll scream
later.

00:04:12.459 --> 00:04:19.000
And that phrase stuck with me ever since.
And I think it strikes the right tone of humor

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:24.360
and irony coming from this Deaf gal, because
as you'll see in my book, I may be Deaf, but

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:28.729
I'm probably one of the loudest people you'll ever meet.

00:04:28.729 --> 00:04:35.729
My good friend and mentor, Henry Winkler,
put it perfectly when he told me, "If you

00:04:35.889 --> 00:04:42.889
will it, it is not a dream."
For me, if you will it, it is not a dream.

00:04:43.589 --> 00:04:48.050
It's about intention.
And for me, even though I was different than

00:04:48.050 --> 00:04:54.650
everyone else, I had the will and the desire
to make something happen for myself.

00:04:54.650 --> 00:04:59.550
And everything else just followed.
But times have changed.

00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:06.550
Though today I'm an actress and a film producer,
as well as an advocate for children and disability-related

00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:12.860
causes, and most recently a dancer on "Dancing
with the Stars" -- I hope you voted for me.

00:05:12.860 --> 00:05:14.809
Did you vote?
Okay.

00:05:14.809 --> 00:05:21.210
I'm also a mother of four.
And as a result, I'm a cook and a car-pool

00:05:21.210 --> 00:05:28.099
driver and a room mother and a conflict mediator,
and a closet organizer and a pretend math whiz.

00:05:28.099 --> 00:05:32.629
Seriously, life is good.

00:05:32.629 --> 00:05:39.629
It's been 23 years since critics said that
I won my Academy Award out of pity and that

00:05:40.129 --> 00:05:44.080
I would never work in Hollywood again simply
because I was Deaf.

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:49.259
And I'm still here.
The barriers that many had predicted would

00:05:49.259 --> 00:05:56.259
stop my career dead in its tracks have virtually
vanished, thanks to many working actors like

00:05:56.499 --> 00:06:02.629
me who are Deaf or differently abled, attitudes
have changed.

00:06:02.629 --> 00:06:07.939
Now, most of the barriers I face are more
humorous than they are distressing.

00:06:07.939 --> 00:06:12.419
Here are a couple of examples.
Once when I was working on a television show

00:06:12.419 --> 00:06:17.289
with Mark Harmon called "reasonable doubts."
Many of you are probably too young to even

00:06:17.289 --> 00:06:22.939
know this program was on the air.
But, anyway, an NBC executive came to visit

00:06:22.939 --> 00:06:26.999
the studio where we were shooting the show.
After watching me work for a little while,

00:06:26.999 --> 00:06:31.349
he said to the executive producer of the show,
you know, that Marlee Matlin is great.

00:06:31.349 --> 00:06:38.349
Is she going to be Deaf for the whole show?
[ Laughter ]

00:06:40.479 --> 00:06:46.129
It's okay, I'm over it.
And once while I was ready to appear live

00:06:46.129 --> 00:06:52.509
on CNN, in front of millions of viewers, as
you know CNN has, the director was counting

00:06:52.509 --> 00:06:57.319
down the seconds, and I was getting my makeup,
Jack was sitting with the reporter on the

00:06:57.319 --> 00:07:01.279
other side of the camera, as we were counting
down, with just three seconds, she leaned

00:07:01.279 --> 00:07:06.710
over to Jack and said, "Could you tell Marlee
that my dog is deaf just like her."

00:07:06.710 --> 00:07:10.169
And suddenly I was live on television, and
I'm thinking, what does she want me to --

00:07:10.169 --> 00:07:12.259
does she want to throw me a bone?
Does she want me to say woof?"

00:07:12.259 --> 00:07:18.719
I don't know.
Okay.

00:07:18.719 --> 00:07:24.159
And this doesn't only happen in Hollywood.
It happened to me a couple of times.

00:07:24.159 --> 00:07:28.099
I don't know about you, those people who are
Deaf, but I'm on a plane, ready for the plane

00:07:28.099 --> 00:07:31.649
to take off.
I'm set, my seat belt is on, and Jack and

00:07:31.649 --> 00:07:34.939
I are signing to each other.
The flight attendant comes over, sees me signing,

00:07:34.939 --> 00:07:39.069
waves, gives me a menu.
As soon as she sees me signing, she grabs

00:07:39.069 --> 00:07:42.839
the menu out of my hand, goes to the galley
and returns with a new menu in Braille.

00:07:42.839 --> 00:07:49.839
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Actually, they have to think

00:07:53.099 --> 00:07:57.050
about it for a moment, too.
And she's like, "Yes, so what's wrong?

00:07:57.050 --> 00:08:01.309
Don't you need the Braille?"
I'm like, "No, I'm Deaf, not blind."

00:08:01.309 --> 00:08:08.309
And then she realizes it, and then I never
see her for the rest of the flight.

00:08:08.659 --> 00:08:14.839
I use these stories not to trivialize the
barriers facing people like myself, because

00:08:14.839 --> 00:08:20.909
every day, there is still discrimination against
differently-abled people and people who are Deaf.

00:08:20.909 --> 00:08:24.439
And whether being in front of the camera,

00:08:24.439 --> 00:08:31.089
out and about, being a mom, or working on
behalf of some of my favorite charities, my

00:08:31.089 --> 00:08:37.340
message has always been the same and one that
I got from my parents, that no matter what

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:44.340
abilities we possess, all of us not only deserve
respect, we deserve to be heard.

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:52.490
In my book, I chronicle that it wasn't always
easy, that sometimes I was made fun of out

00:08:52.490 --> 00:08:57.310
there and sometimes I fell.
But it was all a part of growing up.

00:08:57.310 --> 00:09:04.310
Just because I was Deaf, my parents felt that
I should not live a sheltered life.

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:10.150
And far from it.
They believed that it was important for me

00:09:10.150 --> 00:09:17.150
to embrace life, both the good and the bad.
So even though I danced in front of 25 million

00:09:19.110 --> 00:09:26.110
people each week on "Dancing with the Stars,"
or stood my ground as strong characters who

00:09:26.220 --> 00:09:32.440
just happened to be Deaf on shows like "The
'L' Word" and on "The West Wing," I still

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:37.490
have days when I feel like I'm going out that
front door of my parents' house for the first

00:09:37.490 --> 00:09:42.020
time to prove that I can do anything except
hear.

00:09:42.020 --> 00:09:49.020
And oftentimes I still find myself explaining
that, yes, I do drive a car; and, yes, I can

00:09:49.220 --> 00:09:56.220
have children; and, yes, I am a working actress.
Well, fortunately, with your commitment here

00:09:57.940 --> 00:10:04.940
today to creating greater accessibility, you
at Google have demonstrated that you get it.

00:10:07.430 --> 00:10:11.830
You get it.
Because what you're doing here today with

00:10:11.830 --> 00:10:16.460
YouTube and automatic captioning is nothing
short of extraordinary.

00:10:16.460 --> 00:10:23.460
I cannot tell you how much I've come to rely
on the Internet for my communication needs.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.760
And many others out there, many millions of
others out there.

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:33.450
I'm sure you've probably heard of the irony
of the invention of the telephone, that when

00:10:33.450 --> 00:10:39.810
Alexander Graham Bell, who had a Deaf wife
and a Deaf mother, wanted to find a way to

00:10:39.810 --> 00:10:44.740
help them communicate, he thought of the television
 -- excuse me, the telephone as a tool that

00:10:44.740 --> 00:10:48.680
would help them.
But little did he realize that the telephone

00:10:48.680 --> 00:10:54.380
would be one of the greatest barriers when
it came to communication between the Deaf

00:10:54.380 --> 00:10:56.800
and the hearing world.
Right there.

00:10:56.800 --> 00:11:08.230
Twenty years ago, I lobbied, and I succeeded
in getting the film which inspired me to be

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:14.270
an actress, "The Wizard of Oz," to be closed
captioned for the first time.

00:11:14.270 --> 00:11:21.260
Because captioning was crucial in bringing
the words that you all take for granted

00:11:21.260 --> 00:11:26.700
to my world.
And the following year, in 1990, I took it

00:11:26.700 --> 00:11:33.700
one step further, and I went to Capitol Hill
to lobby on behalf of the legislation that

00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:41.780
all televisions 13 inches or larger should
be equipped with closed captioning technology.

00:11:42.120 --> 00:11:48.810
Like the critics who doubted my ability to
be an actor because, in their eyes, my Deafness

00:11:48.810 --> 00:11:57.120
put me on a level below my peers, TV manufacturers
and programmers thought that millions of Americans

00:11:57.120 --> 00:12:01.660
who were Deaf or hard of hearing didn't deserve
equal access through closed captioned.

00:12:01.660 --> 00:12:08.040
But with the hard work and determination,
we were successful in getting the decoder

00:12:08.040 --> 00:12:13.030
bill passed.
Six years later. And legislation was passed that

00:12:13.030 --> 00:12:19.780
required that all broadcast television be
100% closed captioned.

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:25.780
But like the irony of the invention of the telephone
telephone, the Internet eventually became

00:12:25.780 --> 00:12:32.670
a bigger barrier than one could ever imagine
when it came to closed captioning content on

00:12:32.670 --> 00:12:35.760
broadband.
Here's a good example.

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:42.760
Just last October, the "The Wizard of Oz"
celebrated a wonderful milestone, the 75th

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:48.280
anniversary of its initial release.
And for the first time in broadcast history,

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:53.740
it was going to be streamed live to every
single American who had access to a computer

00:12:53.740 --> 00:12:58.200
for free.
So -- absolutely free.

00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:05.010
So I was eager to share the film with my children,
particularly my then-five-year-old daughter,

00:13:05.010 --> 00:13:12.010
in whose eyes I saw the same sense of wonderment
and excitement that I had when I was 7 watching

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:17.800
the film for the first time about the young
girl with the Ruby slippers who dreamt of

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:23.370
someplace over the Rainbow.
But when I opened up my laptop and hit the

00:13:23.370 --> 00:13:30.370
"play" button, I was horrified to find that
the film that I had lobbied to get closed

00:13:32.170 --> 00:13:37.400
captioned 20 years earlier was shown without
captions.

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:44.400
I was told that the technology was not out
there and that I had to be patient and to

00:13:45.970 --> 00:13:52.970
wait.
Well, as I said, I like to make noise.

00:13:53.560 --> 00:14:00.560
So I tweeted like crazy to the thousands of
followers that I had on Twitter, and I made

00:14:00.950 --> 00:14:07.950
sure that my friends, like Ashton Kutcher
and Alyssa Milano knew what was going on and

00:14:09.320 --> 00:14:11.430
 -- what was going on with closed captions
on the Internet.

00:14:11.430 --> 00:14:16.750
And I encouraged them to re-Tweet.
And they did.

00:14:16.750 --> 00:14:23.750
Then I found out there was actually no problem
with the technology, and, in fact, the technology

00:14:23.910 --> 00:14:29.230
is out there to stream content with closed
captions.

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:32.520
When it came down to the same issue, a lack

00:14:32.520 --> 00:14:39.900
of understanding, it was a lack of understanding,
and a large percentage of manufacturers said

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.870
that -- we said, "You need to provide access
for the millions of users who are Deaf or

00:14:43.870 --> 00:14:48.540
hard of hearing.
So by providing closed captions, they can

00:14:48.540 --> 00:14:52.080
get access."
More importantly, they failed to understand

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:58.050
that original programming had captions, but
that the Internet had to have the captions

00:14:58.050 --> 00:15:01.730
as well.
Eventually, the frustration increased so much,

00:15:01.730 --> 00:15:08.730
because I had to fight to make -- to do what
I did 20 years ago all over again.

00:15:10.360 --> 00:15:16.870
The ultimate irony came during the unveiling
of the celebration of Helen Keller's life.

00:15:16.870 --> 00:15:19.150
There was a statue being unveiled in the capitol
rotunda.

00:15:19.150 --> 00:15:27.850
It was streamed live without captions.
Here we're celebrating and honoring a woman

00:15:27.920 --> 00:15:33.779
who fought for equality and accessibility
over 100 years ago, and who I looked up to

00:15:33.779 --> 00:15:38.070
as a role model, and I wasn't even able to
share the celebration of her life.

00:15:38.070 --> 00:15:45.070
It was simply unacceptable, unacceptable.
But you at Google, you changed all that.

00:15:46.730 --> 00:15:53.730
Just as you did when you pioneered the search
engine, you are helping to ensure the commitment

00:15:53.779 --> 00:15:59.920
and standards and legislation that we work
for in access in broadcast TV are continuing

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:06.310
here with your efforts in getting hundreds
and thousands of videos on YouTube broadcast

00:16:06.310 --> 00:16:13.310
with closed captions.
So today, I am proud to premiere the pilot

00:16:13.770 --> 00:16:20.740
episode of a show that I produced which I
hope will become a series either on network

00:16:20.740 --> 00:16:26.480
or Web, called "My Deaf Family."
And the show chronicles a family from right

00:16:26.480 --> 00:16:33.080
here in the San Francisco Bay Area that is
made up of both Deaf and hearing family members.

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:40.080
It's told from the perspective of 15-year-old
Jared Firl, who is hearing.

00:16:40.860 --> 00:16:46.240
Jared's parents are Deaf, and they work nearby
here at the California School for the Deaf

00:16:46.240 --> 00:16:51.190
in Fremont.
And Jared also has three siblings, two of

00:16:51.190 --> 00:16:57.270
whom are Deaf and one who is hearing.
I like to think of it as a Deaf version of

00:16:57.270 --> 00:17:02.089
'Little People, Big World'.
And I even pitched it to TLC in the hopes

00:17:02.089 --> 00:17:09.089
of creating the first reality show of its
kind ever showing what life is like for millions

00:17:10.329 --> 00:17:15.459
of Americans who are Deaf and hard of hearing.
Unfortunately, TLC seemed more interested

00:17:15.459 --> 00:17:20.959
in doing a show about killing moose with Sarah Palin.

00:17:20.959 --> 00:17:22.589
Fine.
That's okay.

00:17:22.589 --> 00:17:26.189
That's all right.
If TLC won't have me, I figure I'll do it

00:17:26.189 --> 00:17:33.189
my words and using Ms. Palin's words, I'm
going to go rogue and broadcast it on YouTube,

00:17:35.119 --> 00:17:41.960
where I can call the shots and where I can
be guaranteed that the show will be broadcast

00:17:41.960 --> 00:17:46.580
with captions.
Thank you, Google, for making this happen.

00:17:46.580 --> 00:17:53.580
I also want to say that though I may be Deaf,
silence is the last thing the world will ever

00:17:54.539 --> 00:17:58.369
hear from me.
And that the real handicap of Deafness does

00:17:58.369 --> 00:18:04.499
not lie in the ear; it lies in the mind.
Thank you for your commitment to breaking

00:18:04.499 --> 00:18:10.659
through the barriers and providing access
to YouTube through automatic captioning.

00:18:10.659 --> 00:18:17.249
Through your example, you're helping to open
the minds of those who choose to handicap

00:18:17.249 --> 00:18:22.820
millions of people like myself who are Deaf
or hard of hearing and who don't provide closed

00:18:22.820 --> 00:18:29.669
captioning content through broadband.
Your efforts today will guarantee the hard-fought

00:18:29.669 --> 00:18:36.559
victory we won so many years ago can move
forward into the 21st century.

00:18:36.559 --> 00:18:43.559
So without any delay, please enjoy the premiere
of "My Deaf Family" on YouTube.

00:18:48.539 --> 00:18:52.600
But before I say this, hold on, one second.
I want to introduce to you one of the stars

00:18:52.600 --> 00:18:58.830
of "My Deaf Family," of this program, Bridgetta
Bourne-Firl is here with us today.

00:18:58.830 --> 00:19:01.659
Could you please stand up.
[ Applause ]

00:19:01.659 --> 00:19:08.539
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Thank you for coming out,
taking time out of your busy schedule to be

00:19:08.539 --> 00:19:11.860
with us.
I want to thank the children and the students

00:19:11.860 --> 00:19:14.720
from the California School for the Deaf who
are with us today, who came out today with

00:19:14.720 --> 00:19:16.230
us.
[ Applause ]

00:19:16.230 --> 00:19:23.230
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: So just two things.
Enjoy the show, and I'm going to think about

00:19:24.259 --> 00:19:26.259
where to find my glasses so I can read some
more.

00:19:26.259 --> 00:19:28.159
Okay.
Let's go.

00:19:28.159 --> 00:19:32.659
