00:24:40.879 --> 00:24:45.049
it seems the information that's there captioned
isn't moving with captions.

00:24:45.049 --> 00:24:51.730
They're still not captioning it.
HR-3101 is intended to force Internet providers

00:24:51.730 --> 00:24:58.149
to caption what's already been captioned.
So it's applying that law to the Internet.

00:24:58.149 --> 00:25:01.609
There's a lot of complaints.
Well, a lot of it is user-generated.

00:25:01.609 --> 00:25:04.230
We can't caption that.
How are you going to force us to do that?

00:25:04.230 --> 00:25:08.889
I mean, a lot of stuff on YouTube is made
by people who go to YouTube.

00:25:08.889 --> 00:25:11.399
Well, you guys solved that problem with automatic
captions.

00:25:11.399 --> 00:25:15.489
Now it's time for the other people to do that.
So that's what HR-3101 is intended to do.

00:25:15.489 --> 00:25:19.019
We're waiting for the vote, or at least to
be even brought up.

00:25:19.019 --> 00:25:23.889
I'm not familiar with the legislative process.
But we're waiting for sponsors.

00:25:23.889 --> 00:25:27.450
And the health care bill took up a lot of
attention.

00:25:27.450 --> 00:25:31.979
And everybody was focused on that.
So now, hopefully, we can move to this and

00:25:31.979 --> 00:25:34.190
 --
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: I've been working very closely

00:25:34.190 --> 00:25:40.730
with the National Association of the Deaf.
And hoping that their efforts -- I mean, in

00:25:40.730 --> 00:25:43.809
their terms, I'm their spokesperson when it
comes to closed captioning.

00:25:43.809 --> 00:25:47.429
And, hopefully, we can work together to make
sure that this legislation passes.

