00:34:39.500 --> 00:34:42.020
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Thank you.
[ Applause ]

00:34:42.020 --> 00:34:44.780
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Just following up to your
comment.

00:34:44.780 --> 00:34:46.060
Thank you very much for your comment, by the
way.

00:34:46.060 --> 00:34:51.610
Just as you said, you know, all a blind person
can't do is to see, and all a Deaf person

00:34:51.610 --> 00:34:56.620
can't do is to hear.
Otherwise, it's all available.

00:34:56.620 --> 00:35:01.360
I need to ask one question before you do.
Well, no, go ahead with your question first.

00:35:01.360 --> 00:35:04.120
Go ahead.
&gt;&gt;&gt;Actually, I have a question, just from

00:35:04.120 --> 00:35:07.310
a Deaf person's perspective who's here working
at Google.

00:35:07.310 --> 00:35:14.240
You know, I've been here -- starting as a
young person and even now, I've seen many

00:35:14.240 --> 00:35:19.160
challenges and seen how things have changed
over the years with captions on YouTube now.

00:35:19.160 --> 00:35:23.520
And with your presentation today, I'm wondering
if you want to see more captions for Deaf people.

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:30.350
Like, in the future, in ten or so years from

00:35:30.350 --> 00:35:34.300
now, what is it that you're looking for and
ways that we can help Deaf people more?

00:35:34.300 --> 00:35:38.910
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: I get this question every
day, because, as an actor -- in reality, and

00:35:38.910 --> 00:35:43.590
I speak on behalf of all actors -- only 3%
of actors work.

00:35:43.590 --> 00:35:47.740
You know, people who are in the actor's union,
only 3% of us work.

00:35:47.740 --> 00:35:52.080
It's hard to find jobs, regardless of whether
one is Deaf or hearing.

00:35:52.080 --> 00:35:57.040
But if you're talking specifically about Deaf
actors, I think it's probably harder.

00:35:57.040 --> 00:36:00.730
I still struggle myself.
Believe it or not, I still struggle.

00:36:00.730 --> 00:36:06.500
As I stand here today, I had to put up my
video in order to sell it, in order to get

00:36:06.500 --> 00:36:09.650
people to pay attention to it to see how it
would go.

00:36:09.650 --> 00:36:13.620
A lot of Deaf children come up to me and say,
"I want to be an actor like you.

00:36:13.620 --> 00:36:16.460
How is it that I can do it like did you it?
Or how is it?"

00:36:16.460 --> 00:36:20.100
And I say, look, first of all, you need to
finish school.

00:36:20.100 --> 00:36:25.340
If you want to go to college, go to college.
It will certainly do you well in terms of

00:36:25.340 --> 00:36:30.290
your future.
And then see what it leads you to, whatever

00:36:30.290 --> 00:36:37.290
you want to be.
I'm not the president of the Deaf world.

00:36:37.370 --> 00:36:44.370
I'm just an actor who just wants to do movies.
And I'm a person who also happens to advocate

00:36:46.310 --> 00:36:49.990
on behalf of a number of charities, charities
that I believe in, charities that I believe

00:36:49.990 --> 00:36:54.900
need assistance or attention.
And I struggle.

00:36:54.900 --> 00:36:58.680
Sometimes I succeed and sometimes I fail.
But, you know, what, I get back up on my feet

00:36:58.680 --> 00:37:01.560
again and I try.
And I do what I can to find work.

00:37:01.560 --> 00:37:06.660
And it's just a matter -- there are wonderful
Deaf theaters out there, for example, in Los

00:37:06.660 --> 00:37:11.230
Angeles, as well as the National Theater of
the Deaf. Wherever you are in the country,

00:37:11.230 --> 00:37:14.260
there are places Deaf people can go to school, colleges.

00:37:14.260 --> 00:37:19.590
There are so many choices out there.
As much as I would love to be able to own

00:37:19.590 --> 00:37:24.670
a studio like Warner Brothers so everything
is captioned and everybody can have access,

00:37:24.670 --> 00:37:25.530
it doesn't work that way.

00:37:25.530 --> 00:37:32.030
It doesn't work that way.
By the way, my name sign is this (indicating). 

00:37:32.030 --> 00:37:33.530
There you go.

00:37:33.530 --> 00:37:35.130
All right.
Well, I guess that's it.

00:37:35.130 --> 00:37:41.950
&gt;&gt;Susan Wojcicki: How about last comment.
&gt;&gt;&gt;Yeah, just one story that I remember hearing

00:37:41.950 --> 00:37:48.220
when I was younger was, I went to go hear
Vint Cerf, who is one of the founders of the

00:37:48.220 --> 00:37:54.000
Internet protocol that we all use today, TCP,
at George Mason University.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:38:00.390
He spoke about his wife who was Deaf, but
she got a cochlear implant, and the invention

00:38:00.390 --> 00:38:04.320
of the cochlear implant they learned about
on the Internet while they were browsing around

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:09.660
on mosaic Web browser, which is also very
old.

00:38:09.660 --> 00:38:16.340
But -- and this is just an amazing thing to
me to see just the way that these technologies

00:38:16.340 --> 00:38:19.510
impact our lives.
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: It's amazing.

00:38:19.510 --> 00:38:20.550
Thank you.
Thank you for your story.

00:38:20.550 --> 00:38:26.790
See how technology has changed people's lives,
and people are more accepting of others who

00:38:26.790 --> 00:38:30.020
are different and working together and making
things happen.

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:37.020
It's amazing.
&gt;&gt;Susan Wojcicki: Do you want to -- last comment?

00:38:40.530 --> 00:38:45.160
&gt;&gt;&gt;Thank you.
That was very inspiring.

00:38:45.160 --> 00:38:48.700
Just -- I've always loved traveling and sharing
cultures.

00:38:48.700 --> 00:38:53.880
I thought there was a wonderful opportunity
to share some cultural learnings here.

00:38:53.880 --> 00:38:59.100
So I learned from a friend a long time ago
that signing applause is this (indicating),

00:38:59.100 --> 00:39:03.070
so I thought it might be -- for other people
in the room who didn't know, I thought it

00:39:03.070 --> 00:39:07.630
might be interesting for us to share the applause.
&gt;&gt;Susan Wojcicki: Can everyone -- can everyone

00:39:07.630 --> 00:39:09.400
say thank you?
[ Applause ]

00:39:09.400 --> 00:39:14.800
&gt;&gt;Susan Wojcicki: And I'd like to say thank
you to Marlee for coming, and I'd like to

00:39:14.800 --> 00:39:19.630
say thank you for the teams at Google that
work on accessibility and for leading that

00:39:19.630 --> 00:39:22.910
and for making this happen.
It shows what a big impact you can have and

00:39:22.910 --> 00:39:27.740
how you can use technology to make people
who you never meet, people across the world,

00:39:27.740 --> 00:39:29.800
make their lives better.
So thank you.

00:39:29.800 --> 00:39:35.020
Thank you for making this all happen.
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Thank you, Google, for making

00:39:35.020 --> 00:39:38.800
me find my recipes -- looking for recipes
so much easier.

00:39:38.800 --> 00:39:43.700
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Marlee Matlin: Thank you very much.

00:39:43.700 --> 00:39:46.500
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Susan Wojcicki: Great.

